## Description: What is it? (max 1,500 characters)

This is a form of Experimentation that involves the systematic testing of new ideas, approaches, and interventions in a controlled and iterative manner to learn and gather evidence about their effectiveness. UNDP uses this approach to advance sustainable development by piloting, prototyping and evaluating innovative solutions, measuring impact, identifying best practices, and informing evidence-based decision-making, enabling the scaling up of successful interventions and fostering continuous learning and adaptation to achieve sustainable development outcomes.

## Purpose: Why do we use this method or tool for R&amp;D? (max 1,500 characters)

To test two different solutions to provide recommendations for the best solution moving forward. In the case of Eswatini, the RCTs approach was used to test the difference between a disposable and a morden re-usable nappy in order to promote a transition towards more sustainable options

## Summary: Describe in one sentence, what it is and what it does? (max 120 characters)

This method allows for researchers to determine causal relationships

## Instructions: How is it used for R&amp;D? What steps to follow?

A randomized controlled trial (RCT) is a prospective experimental design that randomly assigns participants to an experimental or control group. RCTs are the gold standard for establishing causal relationships and ruling out confounding variables and selection bias. Researchers must be able to control who receives the treatments and who are the controls to use this design.  
For us, this approach began with the identification of the challenge of single use diapers and the havoc that they were causing because of being indiscriminately disposed of in communities. the next step was to map possible solutions, and based on the waste hierarchy, we were able to zoom in on the most sustainable option - the re-usable nappy. This nneded to be tested against the disposable nappy in order to learn certain things that would allow us to facilitate a transition towards the more sustaonable option. participants were then randomly assigned into two groups -  the control and experiment group, where one group was given the re-usable dipaer and the other a disposable diaper. participants were then observed over a three months period and data collected
